{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/posts/2019/8/23/principles-of-dark-noise/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"The Principles of Dark Noise","date":"23 August, 2019","image":"http://media.charliemchapman.com/charlie_and_jack.JPG"},"fields":{"slug":"/posts/2019/8/23/principles-of-dark-noise/"},"html":"<p>At the beginning of this year I started working on my first indie app to release in the App Store called <a href=\"https://darknoise.app\">Dark Noise</a>.  It's an ambient noise app for iPhone and iPad.</p>\n<p>At first, I had a giant list of feature ideas and no idea how to distill them into a focused product. So I started by forcing myself to pick 3 principles to guide the design.</p>\n<p>I eventually landed on these core principles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Configurability</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Targeting pro users who want as many options and hooks to work the app into their workflow as possible</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Speed</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Opening app to playing sound should be as fast as possible with no compromise since this is the 99% use case</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Keep it dark</strong> (expect fat fingers)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Most users will probably be using this in a dark environment, possibly without their glasses on or half asleep.  Keep that in mind.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After creating the principles, I took my list of feature ideas and tried to slot them all into one of those principles.  If they didn't fit, I tossed them in the backlog.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 750px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/45cbd/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 130.6122448979592%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Dark Noise Principles in Action\"\n        title=\"Dark Noise Principles in Action\"\n        src=\"/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/2a7f3/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/1a190/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg 188w,\n/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/992ed/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg 375w,\n/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/2a7f3/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg 750w,\n/static/1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d/45cbd/dark-noise-principles-in-action.jpg 784w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Keeping these principles in mind as I tried to design and form an MVP was really helpful.  I have a tendency to get overly excited by an idea and drop whatever I'm doing and build it.  Often that's a bad idea, but sometimes it's good!</p>\n<p>Whenever I had the thought of adding a bunch of custom app icons referencing podcasts I like, I realized it was something that might actually resonate with the pro users I was targeting.  And seems to have done just that!</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 304px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/35ab14be2a61b67e0ca2088e81797432/22308/dark-noise-app-icons.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 197.36842105263156%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Dark Noise App Icons\"\n        title=\"Dark Noise App Icons\"\n        src=\"/static/35ab14be2a61b67e0ca2088e81797432/22308/dark-noise-app-icons.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/35ab14be2a61b67e0ca2088e81797432/7a748/dark-noise-app-icons.png 188w,\n/static/35ab14be2a61b67e0ca2088e81797432/22308/dark-noise-app-icons.png 304w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 304px) 100vw, 304px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>This also played into my pricing decisions as that market tends to prefer paying up front and is a little more averse to ads.  That's not to say I won't add a free tier in the future (in fact I probably will) but it's something I'm always keeping in mind as I make these decisions.</p>\n<p>Anyway, I'm not an expert at this, heck I'm barely a beginner, but maybe you'll find my thought process interesting nonetheless.</p>\n<p><em>This post is an attempt to make a more permanent record to [this tweetstorm](<a href=\"https://twitter.com/\">https://twitter.com/</a></em>chuckyc/status/1158072465739911168) from a few weeks ago._</p>","excerpt":"At the beginning of this year I started working on my first indie app to release in the App Store called Dark Noise.  It's an ambient noiseâ€¦"}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/posts/2019/8/23/principles-of-dark-noise/"}}}